				</common:classification>
			</classificationInformation>
			<common:generalComment xml:lang="en">Drilling waste is an unavoidable consequence of drilling operations, produced when drilling fluids mix with cuttings and cavings. During drilling, a mixture of oil, gas, and formation water is pumped to the surface. The water is separated into tanks or pits, referred to as 'produced water'. Wastes generated from crude oil and natural gas exploration and production are regulated under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) and state regulations. Abandoned drilling fluid constitutes one of the largest wastes generated during oil and gas exploration and development.</common:generalComment>
